{% extends "@core/docs/_layout.twig" %}

{% block doc_content %}
    <h1>Authentication Setup</h1>
    <p>Rhapsody provides a simple authentication system using Doctrine ORM and the <code>User</code> entity.</p>

    <h2>Prerequisites</h2>
    <p>Make sure you have configured your database connection in <code>.env</code> and installed Doctrine.</p>

    <h2>Creating the Users Table</h2>
    <p>When the login page is visited, the authentication middleware ensures the <code>`users`</code> table exists. If it doesn't, the table and necessary columns will get automatically created:
        <ul>
            <li><var><strong>user_id</strong></var> varchar(255) NOT NULL</li>
            <li><var><strong>name</strong></var> varchar(50) NOT NULL</li>
            <li><var><strong>email</strong></var> varchar(100) NOT NULL</li>
            <li><var><strong>password</strong></var> varchar(255) NOT NULL</li>
            <li><var><strong>created_at</strong></var> datetime NOT NULL DEFAULT current_timestamp()</li>
        </ul>
        <em>Table data: ENGINE=InnoDB DEFAULT CHARSET=utf8mb4 COLLATE=utf8mb4_unicode_ci</em>
    </p>

    <div class="bg-red-100 border-l-4 border-red-500 text-red-700 p-4">
        <strong><span class="text-red-700">WARNING:</span></strong> If you already have an existing users table, the application will assume that the above columns exist. If you plan to use the built-in 
        authentication system, you must make sure the columns exist <strong>as defined</strong> in the above.
    </div>

    <h2>Using the Auth Controller</h2>
    <p>The framework includes a <code>AuthController</code> with routes for login, registration, and logout. Make sure the routes are registered in your <code>web.php</code>:</p>
    <pre><code>$router->get('/login', [AuthController::class, 'showLoginForm']);
$router->post('/login', [AuthController::class, 'login']);
$router->get('/register', [AuthController::class, 'showRegistrationForm']);
$router->post('/register', [AuthController::class, 'register']);
$router->post('/logout', [AuthController::class, 'logout']);</code></pre>

    <h2>Middleware Protection</h2>
    <p>To protect routes, use the <code>auth</code> middleware:</p>
    <pre><code>$router->get('/dashboard', [DashboardController::class, 'index'])->middleware('auth');</code></pre>

    <h2>Customising the User Entity</h2>
    <p>You can extend or modify the <code>App\Entities\User</code> class to add additional fields. After changes, update the table schema using the Doctrine schema tool:</p>
    <pre><code class="language-bash">php rhapsody doctrine:schema:update --force</code></pre>
    <p>Or create a migration for production.</p>
{% endblock %}